        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="x-oldsun-Latn">
                <p>
         <lb n="1"/><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball">Ø</g><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball">Ø</g> vaṁ<unclear>ṅa</unclear> <unclear>p</unclear>un· I<unclear>n</unclear>i sakakala, pr<unclear>ə</unclear>bu ratu purane pun·, ḍivas·tu
         <lb n="2"/><choice><sic>ḍyi</sic><corr>ḍyǝ</corr></choice>, viṅaran· prəbu guru ḍe<unclear>va</unclear>ta p<choice><sic>ra</sic><corr>u</corr></choice>n· ḍivas·tu ḍyə ḍiṅaran· sri
         <lb n="3"/>baduga maharaja, ratu ha<unclear cert="low">j</unclear>i ḍi pakvan· pajajaran· sri sa<unclear>ṁ</unclear> ratu ḍe<lb 
	n="4" break="no"/>vata pun·</p> <p> ya nu ñusuk· na pakvan· ḍyə Anak· rahyi ḍeva nis·<lb 
	n="5" break="no"/>kala, sa siḍa mok·ta ḍi gunuṁ tiga, qə<supplied reason="omitted">ñ·</supplied>cu rahyiṁ <unclear>n</unclear>is·kala vas·tu
        <lb n="6"/>ka<unclear>ca:</unclear>na, saṁ siḍa mok·ta ka nusa laraṁ, </p> <p> ya syi nu <unclear>ñ</unclear>yin· sakaka<lb 
	n="7" break="no"/>la, gugun<unclear>uṅ</unclear>an·, <unclear>ṅa</unclear>balay·,, ñyin· samiḍa, ñyin· saṁ hyi talaga <supplied reason="lost" evidence="paralel">va</supplied><lb 
	n="8" break="no"/>R̥na mahavijaya, </p> <p> ya s<supplied reason="lost">yi pun· </supplied>,,  </p> <p> <g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball">Ø</g><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball">Ø</g> I saka, pañca pan·ḍa<lb 
	n="9" break="no"/>va ṅ<unclear>ə</unclear>ban· bumi <g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball">Ø</g><g type="symbol" subtype="tennisball">Ø</g>
                </p>
              
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="1">
                      	<lem>vaṁ<unclear cert="low">ṅa</unclear> <unclear>p</unclear>un·</lem>
		<rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">vaṁ na pun</rdg>
		<note>On the shape of <foreign>ṅa</foreign>, see <foreign>ṅabalay</foreign> in l. 7.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                  	<lem><choice><sic>ḍyi</sic><corr>ḍyǝ</corr></choice>, viṅaran·</lem>
		<rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">diya viṅaran</rdg>
		<note>It is clear that there is a punctuation between <foreign>ḍyi</foreign> and <foreign>viṅaran</foreign> from the estampages. Hasan Djafar suggests to emend <foreign>viṅaran</foreign> to <foreign>diṅaran</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                       	<lem>p<choice><sic>ra</sic><corr>u</corr></choice>n·</lem>
		<rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">prana</rdg>
		<note>Hasan Djafars reading seems impossible to us, for there is unmistakably a sign between the <foreign>n</foreign> and the following <foreign>ḍi</foreign>, and this sign can only be a paten or punctuation. We feel compelled to emend because no word <foreign>pran</foreign> seems to exist in Sundanese or Javanese.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                                    <lem>ḍyə ḍiṅaran·</lem>
                                    <note>It would be possible to read <foreign>dyəṁ ḍiṅaran</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="4">
                                    <lem>ñusuk· na</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">ñusuk·na</rdg>
                                    <note>All predecessors have by their non-insertion of a space between <foreign>ñusuk</foreign> and <foreign>na</foreign> implied that <foreign>na</foreign> is a pronominal clitic, but it seems more convincing to take it as article <foreign xml:lang="x-oldsun-Latn">na</foreign> (<bibl><ptr target="Hardjadibrata2003_01"/><citedRange>547</citedRange></bibl>).</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="4">
                                    <lem>rahyi</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">rahiyaṁ</rdg> 
                                    <note>We do not see the <foreign>anusvāra</foreign>/<foreign>cecak</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>sa siḍa</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">saṁ sida</rdg> 
                                    <note>Hasan Djafar explains that the <foreign>anusvāra</foreign>/<foreign>cecak</foreign> is present although hard to read. We are inclined to assume that it is absent. Cf. the cases of <foreign>sa ratu</foreign> and <foreign>rahyi</foreign> for <foreign>saṁ ratu</foreign> and <foreign>rahyiṁ</foreign> (= <foreign>rahiyaṁ</foreign>) above. </note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>mok·ta</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">mok·ta</rdg>
                                    <note>We find a special <foreign>ka</foreign> with stroke underline that represents <foreign>paten</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>gunuṁ</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">guna</rdg>
                                    <note>There can be no doubt about our reading. See the toponym Gunuṅ Tiga in the <title>Carita Parahyaṅan</title><!-- Arlo: interesting that you decided to use <title>; our EG does not yet say anything aboit how to cite primary (non-epigraphic) sources, but we will address this in a next version; keep <title> for now --> as cited by Pleyte (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="Pleyte1911_01"/><citedRange>176</citedRange></bibl>).</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem>qə<supplied reason="omitted">ñ·</supplied>cu</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">I<supplied reason="omitted">ñ·</supplied>cu</rdg>
                                    <note>Hasan Djafar reads <foreign>Icu</foreign> and proposes to emend as <foreign>iñcu</foreign>. We see that it is more likely a <foreign>pepet</foreign> rather than <foreign>hulu</foreign> above <foreign>aksara</foreign> <foreign>A</foreign>.</note> 
                    </app>
                    <app loc="5">
                                    <lem><unclear>n</unclear>is·kala</lem>
                                    <rdg source="HasanDjafar2011_01">nis·kala</rdg>
                                    <note>The first consonant is very hard to read as <foreign>n</foreign>, but that is what is must be.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="6">
                                    <lem>nusa laraṁ</lem>
                                    <note>This place is mentioned in CP21v: <foreign>Aya na səvə prəbu vaṁṅi ṅaran·na Iñana prəbu nis·kala vas·tu kañcana nu surup· di nusa §§ laraṁ</foreign> “There is a king’s son, his name is fragrant, he is Prebu Niskala Wastu Kancana who has been burried in the Nusa Larang”.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="7">
                                    <lem><unclear>ṅa</unclear>balay·</lem>
                                    <note>The first consonant is unclear. If we are to follow Hasan Djafar who reads <foreign>ṅabalay</foreign>, then this means that at the beginning of line 1, we also need to read <foreign>ṅa</foreign>.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="7-8">
                                    <lem>talaga <supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previousedition">va</supplied>R̥na</lem>
                                    <note>Restoration proposed by Hasan Djafar. Cf. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Pleyte1911_01"/><citedRange>172</citedRange></bibl>, citation from FCP.6a: <foreign>ti saṁ hyiṁ talaga vaṙna miñak· hanət· sagomboṁ Uyaḥ salave kəlek· lilitan· salave tək·tək· boEḥ putiḥ sakayuḥ hayam· sakurən·</foreign> “From Talaga Warna: essential oil one gombong, salt 25 <foreign>kəlek</foreign>, waist cloth 25 <foreign>təktək</foreign>, white cloth one <foreign>kayuh</foreign>, chicken one <foreign>kurən</foreign>”.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>                
           
           <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng" resp="part:adgu part:argr"><!-- Arlo" use @resp, see EG 9.2 and 10.6 --> <!-- Adit: I dont know how to combine two responsables, is this correct? -->
                <p><foreign>Om pun</foreign>. This is the decree/message of his majesty the king of old, inaugurated here with the name Prabu Guru Dewata, <supplied reason="subaudible">and also</supplied> inaugurated here with the name Sri Baduga Maharaja, king of kings in Pakwan Pajajaran, Sri Sang Ratu Dewata, is inaugurated here.</p>  
                <p>He is the one who demarcates the Pakwan here, <supplied reason="subaudible">being</supplied> the child of Rahyang Dewa Niskala, he one who was released at Gunung Tiga; grandchild of Rahyang Niskala Wastu Kancana, the one who was released to Nusa Larang.</p> 
                <p>He, that one, produced the decree <seg cert="low">in the shape of a mountain</seg>, made hard the ground with stones; he produced fire-wood; he produced the holy Color Lake.</p> 
                <p>Victorious, was he! In the year: the five Pandawas carry the earth <supplied reason="subaudible">i.e. in 1<seg cert="low">2</seg>55 Śaka</supplied></p>
          </div>
